My dad made me who I am today. He taught me everything from shooting to dog training and instilled in me the values that I hope to pass to my son. He hit a bit of a rough patch about a month ago when he was diagnosed with stage 3 colon cancer. My dad is an extremely humble man and will never ask for help so I’m gonna do it for him.  He’s a tough SOB and your help will mostly be helping my mom, she’s a lot more stressed about it than he is. I’ve loved interacting with all of you guys every day and our family would deeply appreciate your support. I’ve posted the gofundme for my dad in my story and in my bio

I am at an absolute loss for words from the outpouring of support you guys have given my family. The world is in the gutter right now and it’s easy to have a negative outlook but the past 24 hours have reminded me that there are a ton of genuinely good people out there. Thanks to you my dad will be well taken care of and the financial burden has been significantly lightened. I know each one of you will be blessed for your sacrifice. We are extremely grateful for all of you. Thank you

Get good at destroying evil, let me explain. We will ultimately fail if we wait to destroy evil when it manifests in violence upon the innocent. We must first eradicate it in our homes. Evil is truly vanquished when it cannot find footing in our most vital institutions. Love and cherish your spouse, give your sons and daughters a standard to strive for. How you interact with your spouse is seared into the subconscious of your children and will have a lasting effect on how they will pursue and ultimately treat and provide for their future spouse. Talk with your children, many of life’s problems are lessened simply by knowing that someone cares and is thinking of you. Teach strong values, religion is a controversial topic but it has given me purpose and direction and that’s something that I will strive to give to my children. And last get really good at destroying the physical evil, carry everywhere and train often. Your gun is your sword, wield it with devastating speed and accuracy. Stay fit and vigilant.

I’ll jump on this topic. Does fitness effect your shooting ability? I say yes but it’s kind of a nuanced question. I say it’s one of the building blocks of becoming a better shooter not the keystone to higher performance. It will in no way have a negative effect on your shooting ability (or anything in your life for that matter) good health and discipline will have a positive effect on literally every aspect of your life. I’ve gone on stints where I don’t work out form months and my quality of life changes drastically compared to when I’m lifting consistently as well as watching what I’m eating. What are your thoughts?

It’s been a long time since you had a few minutes of peace and quiet. Reminds you of the days of reading about wars and rebellions on distant continents and being able to just put your phone down to escape it. You didn’t know it then but your government had been at war and your nation had already been infiltrated and attacked quite a few times. The train derailments we’re just the beginning. Russian and Chinese agents had started by attacking American infrastructure to test the media and governments reaction and of course the big corporations were quick to cover it up. The railways were a relatively easy target and it wasn’t hard to locate the hazmat car’s schedule and find an ideal “derailment” location next to a major waterway. No one ever even questioned the frequency and accuracy of these accidents being toxic and how devastating they were to our waterways. Along with the political turmoil and our distraction in Eastern Europe we were ripe for attack. The imperial hubris of our “leaders” had sealed our fate. The Mal you found eating the carcass of a downed J-20 pilot had become your only form of companionship. Life had become so much more complicated but at the same time it was painfully simple. Your moment of respite and reflection is shattered as a round cracks over your head, the painful simplicity of your new life manifesting itself again. Kill or be killed

Yes gear can always fail but in the event that we are all training for, I am the one that needs the most maintenance and is the most vulnerable. The past few months have been a huge learning experience with taking my diet and physical fitness very seriously. Seeing how much more I can do even after thinking I was pretty athletic. Buy and train with the best gear that you can but make sure that your physical state lives up to the standards you are putting on your gear. @garand_thumb said it best “if you’re not fit, you’re gonna die”

A good holster should do 3 things. 1. Conceal well. I’ve been carrying full size guns for 9 years and have had no issues with printing from any one my tier 1 concealed holsters. 2. Be consistent. The clips and geometry of the holster should provide a stable platform what will not move throughout the day. 3. Perform. A good holster will conceal well and give you ample purchase hight to establish a quick and strong grip on the handgun every time. When the holster does these three things really well all you have to do is train hard and maximize your potential. You should never be limited by your gear. Since the tier 1 page got suspended don’t forget to follow the backup @tier1concealedofficial and the link to purchase the axis elite that I use is in my bio. Train hard friends and carry everywhere

10 year old sawyer would be proud. When I was 10 my dad brought home an RWS Diana 45 air rifle. I put no less than a million pellets through that German tac driver. One winter I set some clay pigeons out in our pasture (approximately 80 yards from the living room window) I would open the window just enough and use a towel as my shooting bag. Figuring out my holds in the harsh Idaho wind and shattering each clay one by one would be the start of my addiction to long range shooting. What I wasn’t aware of was those pellets were skipping on the hard top layer of snow and traveling another 100 yards and embedding themselves into my neighbors siding. That next summer he came over with a handful of pellets and asked my dad if he knew anything about them and how they ended up in the side of his house. Building this @fx.airguns impact M3 at @utah_airguns and shooting it in their range brought back fond memories. Air rifles have advanced substantially in that last 20 years and I’m excited to show you what they are capable of
